      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's correct. If the load increases at the very tip of the balcony, the torque indeed increases significantly due to the length multiplier effect. The further from the pivot point (the anchor point), the greater the torque produced by a given force.\n\nRegarding your concern about the internal stress due to non-uniform load distribution, it's a bit of both material strength and the anchor point's ability to hold that moment. The material strength is crucial because it determines the balcony's ability to withstand the internal forces without failing. If the material is too weak, it might crack or bend under the stress.\n\nHowever, the anchor point's ability to hold the moment is equally important. If the anchor point cannot provide sufficient resistance to the torque, the balcony could still fail, regardless of the material strength. The anchor point must be designed to handle the maximum expected torque, which includes considerations for the worst-case load distribution scenario.\n\nIn summary, both the material strength and the anchor point's ability to hold the moment are critical for maintaining structural integrity. The design must ensure that the materials can handle the stresses and that the anchor point is robust enough to resist the maximum torque.",
